          "question_format": "mcq",
          "question": "The curve $C$ has equation $x = 4\\cos 2y$. At $Q\\left(2, \\frac{\\pi}{6}\\right)$, what is the gradient of the normal to $C$?",
          "options": [
            "$4\\sqrt{3}$",
            "$-4\\sqrt{3}$",
            "$-\\frac{1}{4\\sqrt{3}}$",
            "$\\frac{1}{4\\sqrt{3}}$"
          ],
          "correct_option": "A",
          "explanation": "$\\frac{dx}{dy} = -8\\sin 2y$, so $\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{1}{-8\\sin 2y}$. At $y=\\frac{\\pi}{6}$: $\\sin\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$, giving $\\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{1}{4\\sqrt{3}}$. The normal gradient is the negative reciprocal: $4\\sqrt{3}$.",
          "diagram_required": "none"
        }
      ]
